text:
after taking a month break, a new episode of the summer friends podcast will air this thursday. joining me is laporte county sheriff's office detective jennifer rhine-walker. jen is an unsung hero. among many things, jen is the primary investigator in charge of sex crimes in the county. we had a 90-minute conversation (that i'm working hard to whittle down to 60 minutes) about her journey to becoming a detective, the #metoo movement, and being a female in a male-dominated profession. 
summer friends are friends whose lives intersect over a shared season and place. the summer friends podcast is a regular conversation hosted by nate loucks. each episode will be one hour of equal parts storytelling, interview, and education. episodes are available on nateloucks.net or through itunes, google play, tunein, and other podcasting platforms.

text:
in the nest i was holding my 3 year old self. 
that's the first memory of the abuse. 
and, i had no one to hold me and make me feel safe. 
i just wanted my mom. 
i thought she could keep me safe. 
not my adopted one. 
but, the one that gave me up. 
i remember how she felt.
i remember the love that i did feel for the small moments that there had been. 
i wanted to go back because it felt so unsafe to be where i was. 
all that i really wanted was her. 
i was mad because the abuse and the drugs that i had been exposed to at an early age had physically hurt me. 
she hurt me through disappointment. 
they hurt me by never listening to me. 
and, i hurt myself because i was hurting. 
it was gut wrenching to experience all of that through those ages. 
no one told me that i was going to be ok. 
no one understood me. 
no one heard me when i told them 'i think he practices on me'.
no one protected me.
and, no one held me with the love that i needed. 
all that i want to tell that little girl is....
i love you. 
everything is ok. 
there is nothing wrong with you or the way you felt. 
it was real and i believe you. 
i will always be here to hold you and keep you safe. .  thank you to @thenestproject for being bold enough to express your art and show us what it is to have a place to feel held by ourselves in this world. ğŸ¦ŠğŸ’‹

text:
please remember ccasa and survivors this colorado gives day on tuesday, december 4th. whether it's $10 or $100, every donation helps. for your convenience, you can even schedule your donation ahead of time at https://www.coloradogives.org/ccasa

itâ€™s been a busy year! nationally, the #metoo movement has brought to light the pervasiveness of sexual harassment and assault. at the same time, title ix protections for survivors on campuses are being threatened. here in colorado, reports and credible findings of sexual harassment at our state legislature have started much needed conversations and work to address these issues. we need your help to keep working to ensure survivors are protected and can receive the support they need to heal. "i support ccasa because every single day, across the entire state, it makes a positive difference for survivors and the organizations that support them." - alison, ccasa board chairperson

adam had always enjoyed spending time with his uncle, and would often look forward to sleepovers when they could have extended time together. on one of these occasions when he was 14, their normal activities turned abusive. he was confused by his uncleâ€™s actions; nothing like this had happened before.

for the next four years, adam continued to struggle, both with the physical abuse and the emotional pain it brought him. â€œi took steps to prevent the pain, but a part of me thought that was how he loved me.â€
adam did not report the assault or tell anyone from his family. he feared that he wouldnâ€™t be believed and that the truth would destroy his family. â€œi think thereâ€™s a stigma attached to it that, â€˜oh, youâ€™re a man, you should have been able to fend him off.â€™â€ it wasnâ€™t easy to recover from the abuse, but adam found that talking about what happened to a supportive network of friends and family helped him to heal. â€œthe experience i have had in the recovering from the abuse is [that] he did not win. i have not allowed myself to be defined by the abuse.â€

text:
breakups suck!
.
they are painful, messy, and traumatic, and leave your head spinning, wondering big questions like â€œwhat now?â€ and â€œhow do i actually move on?â€
.
when severing ties with someone who was once the most important person in your life, it can feel like you are still being pulled back into the relationship or to that person almost like to an addiction that has just been ended. just as there is help for ending other addictions, clean will be your greatest resource to mending your broken heart and ending the cycle of your relationship.
.
in clean, you will be guided through a twelve-step program to free yourself from the chains of the relationship and begin to see that this breakup is the catalyst for you to begin living your best, most creative, and exciting life yet. navigating through the steps will include:
.
â€¢ embracing the suck and learning to wade through the really hard emotions
.
â€¢learning the reasons why no contact with your ex for a period of time is for your own benefit
.
â€¢exploring exciting ideas for where to channel your newfound time and energy post-breakup
.
through journal questions and action steps, you will be guided along through every chapter. at the end of this proven program, you will be able to finally stand tall and say, â€œi am clean.â€
.
.
my new book is finally out! you can order through the link in my bio! i wrote this book after a devastating breakup and it shows you all the tricks, tools and tips i used to finally become fully clean of my ex and my relationship. whether you are getting divorced, breaking up with a partner or simply canâ€™t let go of your ex ... this book was written for you! iâ€™m excited to share this with you. as carrie fisher once said and is quoted in the first few pages of this book:
"take your broken heart, make it into art."
.
thatâ€™s precisely what i did. if you grab a copy, tag me in your journey through the 12 steps and please leave an honest review on amazon for me. ğŸ™ğŸ½ğŸ’–
.
i canâ€™t wait to hear from you! happy reading my friends!

text:
yes, absolutely, i'm still accepting and posting our stories. email, dm, or form at link in profile.
.
with #twft52 launching soon (working on providing the details, i promise!), my website under some much-needed construction, sidebars, collaborations, etc, not to mention the rest of life, i've been spreading myself a bit thin lately. a few of you have asked privately, so i wanted to clarify here. sharing other survivor stories was central to my early mission, and while my work is evolving faster than i can keep up, i will *always* be a safe place for you to make your voice heard. even if you've published in your own accounts, or elsewhere. you get to say it as often as you need to, wherever you can, if that helps. and more than simply sharing, it's important to me to foster thoughtful conversation about the dynamics around our experiences.
.
so yes. please do share your story, and allow me the honor of giving it safe place to live. you deserve that, and so much more.
.
@thewordforthis

a beautiful depiction of the 7 major chakras. starting from the top of the head and ending with the sexual organs, we find the colorful portals of light. the word chakra translates to wheel of light. you can think of these as your seven major energy centers that reflect the emotional and spiritual health of the body. to name them, beginning with the top of the head, we have the crown chakra. from there we move to the third eye, then the throat chakra, heart chakra, solar plexus, sacral, and finally the root chakra. we will speak over time in depth about all of these. contrary to popular belief, chakras are a scientifically proven to be energy centers that emit movement in the body surrounding the auric field. interested in proving to yourself that these portals really exist? hold a pendulum, or even a small stone tied to a string, just an inch or two over the third eye - or the center of the eyebrows. be still, close your eyes for a few moments and you will see when you open them again that the pendulum will be swinging in a clockwise or counter clockwise direction. repeat this exercise over all 7 major chakras points. before you know it, youâ€™ll have given yourself your first energy reading. âœ¨

text:
trigger warning
this is my piece i titled "impact" i made for class this semester addressing the topic of how trauma affects mental health. i'm nervous to share it, but it was well  recieved by my class and i'm very proud of it. my work is meant to show the impact of sexual and mental abuse on a person over time. it isn't just "this happened, it was bad, and now it's over", it's "this happened years and years ago, and it was so bad that it's still not really over". left to right, top to bottom, they're titled "anxiety", "abuse", "ed", and "depression". these are the experiences i developed from my trauma, things that i had done to me, and things were told to me about my experience. i was not only in a bad relationship, but i was blamed for it and criticized because i didn't feel safe to tell the truth, so i spent years holding it in and believing that, spending my developing years soaked in shame. it's not a very light hearted project, but it's something that i'd been thinking about for a long time beforehand. this is my truth. most of the affects aren't visible from the outside, and people don't always realize the way they speak or the things they do leave that lasting of an affect. treat people with love, and respect their stories. don't victim blame, don't perpetuate hateful views and actions, and don't continue ignorant to the consequences of your actions or the people around you. i'm now in an incredibly happy, supportive relationship and i surround myself with only the people wishing me the best intentions, but that doesn't mean it's just done, still. some things don't just happen and are done with.
i'm not pro anything in these pictures, these just reflect my own experience. life is cruel, but nobody is alone in it. you are not your trauma, and even if you can't love yourself, someone else loves you. be kind and gentle with our fragile hearts â¤ï¸
(this is not me, i used an anonymous model, thank you to them for helping me with this project)

i have spoken on quite a few posts in which women say why a man will be with a woman for many years then break up. he will marry another women doing everything the ex wanted of him and marry her in 6 months.
ğŸ‘‚
ğŸ‘‚
the main reason is because she lacked emotional maturity. many women from ages 25-55 aren't as mature emotionally as they think. most women don't have an emotional maturity age that matches their earth age. speaking from experience, when i dated women under 35, i usually had a difficult time with their emotional immaturity. one reason is because i dealt with many cougars in my youth, 40+ in age.
ğŸ‘‚
ğŸ‘‚

text:
@arimelber â¤ @seanhannity ğŸ’ªğŸ˜ğŸ‘ wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

@arimelber â¤ @seanhannity ğŸ’ªğŸ˜ğŸ‘ this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading â€“ which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs â€“ and he listened to wylieâ€™s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridgeâ€™s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas itâ€™s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

text: i had my first encounter with trolls, arguing for the sake of arguing, making rude statements for the sake of it. i check on their account to see if i can understand who they are and they barely exist. no pictures or are hard right conservatives. i recall standing in front of the mirror when i realized this is the fire inside me, this is my passion, i knew i would say things that are not going to resonate with some, in fact even many. i recall in that moment starring into my own eyes and asking out loud... "are you ready for this?" ... my resounding answer from deep within was yes. i'm not backing down, i will say what needs to be said. my value is not based on the comments of internet trolls or insensitive, right, conservative, mysogenistic patriarchal values. i am grounded in my self, i am confident in my voice and grateful for the opportunity to share what needs to be shared. i lost a shit ton of followers when i first changed this account. i knew that would happen, and that not everyone would be ready to hear what i have to say. sadly those are the ones we need to reach the most. i am grateful to each of you who have reached out personally to me, to share your stories, to express gratitude for say what needs to be said. i may waiver, bobble or stumble.. i am inherently a sensitive person. but as for the trolls... meh ğŸ¤·ğŸ¤¦... you waste your time.

text:
my experience: 
i went back to a guys house. i was drunk. i said to him on the way back that me going back to his didnâ€™t mean anything. he said that was fine.
as soon as we got in he came on to me. i said no. i told him i didnâ€™t feel comfortable but he continued. he told me how â€˜unfairâ€™ i was being and how he didnâ€™t â€˜rate me as a personâ€™ for not wanting to carry on. i donâ€™t know how many times i asked him to stop. 
i started to cry. i felt so pressured. i said iâ€™m sorry, i just donâ€™t want to. i sat up and he put his hand round my throat and pushed me back down. he got on top of me. i started to cry again. i said iâ€™m sorry i just donâ€™t want to do this. he hit me. 
i was so scared, i didnâ€™t know what to do. i froze.
when it ended he laid down next to me. i was in so much shock i just laid there too. i waited until he fell asleep and then i texted my friend and told her i needed help.
it took me over an hour to get away from him, i had to convince him to let me go. he shouted at me and was aggressive.
i hadnâ€™t realised what had just happened. i didnâ€™t realise what he had done to me.
luckily i went to the hospital the next day. at that moment i wasnâ€™t ready to admit to myself that i had really been sexually assaulted, i was in no way ready to go to the police. 
three weeks later i rang the police and made my report. after it was done i felt so much relief, i felt that i had power again and i could now start to heal. 
i was lucky to have amazing friends who helped me through every single stage. more than anything though, i was lucky i went to the hospital the next day. i was lucky to have a friend who told me about the specialised sexual assault hospital called the havens. i was so lucky to know where to turn to because if i hadnâ€™t i would have buried my head in the sand.
what i went through was horrible but it has made me stronger. i am determined to help others; to make sure everyone knows what consent is; that everyone knows where to turn if this happens to them; everyone has someone who will believe them.

text:
it was in south africa that everything hit me. 
in this mall exactly.

i was invited to volunteer alongside hillsong as they brought 200 kids from a very improvised township, outside of cape town, to the movies. for most of them, it was their first time. the look on their faces when some saw the buildings, the lights, stores, the escalatorâ€¦ it was without words. they had never even seen such things.

i gravitated instantly to the kids in the wheelchairs. i too, once, was in a wheelchair. only for a year and a half, and in the united states, so our experiences were gravely different. but there was still some shared emotions that i could relate to.

at one moment, one of the little girls who seemed to really cling to me (and i to her), had to use the bathroom. with the language barrier, it took me a second to realize what she needed but i quickly was able to push her over into the ladies room.

pushing someone else in a wheelchair. how grateful to be on the other side of that. to be the one who was able to help someone else., after all the helped i had been given.

we got into the bathroom and she then looked at me. without any words exchanged or even much thought, i understood what she needed immediately. because i had once been in her position, not able to use my legs and had to rely on others to help me. a lot of the times with some of the most humiliating things. 
so i jumped right in!

i knew exactly how to work the wheelchair, i knew how to assist and help her to properly transfer onto the toilet. i then waited for her to be done, busying myself with my back turned.  when she was done, i helped her further and then pulled up her pants and transferred her back into the wheelchair. maneuvering the chair in front of the sink so she could then wash her hands. 
so many feelings and emotions came over me. it was as if, everything i had been through, had prepared me to give from a deeper place of compassion.â€¨
we must always give from a place of compassion.

text:
harassment

employers have a duty to prevent harassment of one colleague by another. harassment involves being subjected to unwanted behaviour with the intent or effect of intimidation, hostility, offense or humiliation, and can take the form of name calling, homophobic comments or insults, ridicule, ostracization, pranks and practical jokes, and physical abuse.
as well as ensuring a working environment where colleagues are protected against harassment occurring, employers have a duty to act on a complaint when it is brought forward (whether by the victim or witness). refusal to do so risks claims being brought against an organisation for allowing this behaviour to exist.

victimisation

if a victim or witness speaks out against discrimination, harassment or bullying, they should not be punished for doing so â€“ indeed, employees are protected by law against victimisation. however, worryingly this does occur and in turn feeds the cycle of silence, fear and inequality suffered by certain individuals. we need to break this cycle.

text:
why is making a schedule so important?

when you schedule something, statistics have shown, that you are more likely to accomplish it.

if you have a lot of things to accomplish and you do not write a list or make a schedule you may struggle to accomplish them or even forget to do some of them.

when you make a list and complete a task and mark off the list each task, it sends a message to your brain, it creates a pattern of accomplishment and that enables you to accomplish your goals!

having a budget is the same concept as having a schedule. statistics have shown, that when we plan or assign things they are more likely to be accomplished!

food

drinks
presents

#repost from @officialmuterkelly with @regram.app ... via @aliyasking for @essence magazine.
.
.
in the summer of 1984, i was sexually assaulted by a 17-year-old camp counselor. i was 12 years old. the counselor was from my hometown and i saw him every day at camp and then every day in school for the next year until he graduated.
.
if i saw this man on the street today, would i say a word to him? absolutely not. would i visit his church? never. for me, this man is canceled. forever. since 1984. i wouldnâ€™t say i hate him, but i would never want anything to do with him, his family, his friends. i know exactly what canceling someone looks like and when it came to my abuser, i had no problem doing so.
.
if my attacker had been #rkelly, would i listen to his music? absolutely not. i wouldnâ€™t be able to stomach a single note. i wouldnâ€™t be able to watch his videos or see him perform. he would be canceled.
.
and yet i still listened to his music. why wouldnâ€™t i? the man has been called a musical genius, serving as a bridge from classic soul artists like #samcooke and #steviewonder. of course, celebrity worship has always been a tricky game. and one could argue that @rkelly was no different from so many others.... i separated the artist from the art.
.
i finally understand, this is exactly whatâ€™s happening to scores of black women who have reported that r. kelly abused them in various ways. these women live in a world that simply doesnâ€™t seem to care about their allegations. a world that separates the artistÂ  from the art.
.
.
right is right and wrong is wrong, and iâ€™m way late to this campaign. but better late than never, because power in numbers has always been the source of our progressâ€”from slave revolts to civil rights sit-ins to the #metoo movement. though i finally hit the #muterkelly button, it should have been sooner; i think many will say the same as the movement continues to grow. there is no room for nuance anymore. the truth is, there never was. so, for my daughtersâ€™ sake and for women everywhere, i will no longer separate the artist from his art. .
.

text:
@theyoungturks â¤ @seanhannity ğŸ’ªğŸ˜ğŸ‘ bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
@arimelber â¤ @katyturnbc ğŸ’ªğŸ˜˜ğŸ‘ qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
#16days of activism against gender-based violence. 
the time for change is here and now.

text:
@arimelber â¤ @katyturnbc ğŸ’ªğŸ˜˜ğŸ‘ wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

@arimelber â¤ @maddowshow ğŸ’ªğŸ˜˜ğŸ‘ bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

@arimelber â¤ @lastwordmsnbc ğŸ’ªğŸ˜˜ğŸ‘ qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

she was small when it happened. the thing she shouldn't talk about. in that moment she became the sacrifice; the offering of a sick man. what she was before no longer lived. she was a self not herself. 
when she became bigger, they could smell it on her. but, it was her fault. she wanted it - i'm sure. 
she thought someone could make her better - could replace that part of her. she didn't know that part was dead - she sometimes still doesn't know. 
she got better. she survived. she is surviving. she protects herself. she is defensive. 
you are oversensitive. 
she makes things from the part of her that cannot be replaced. these are her own sacrifices. and when she shows them, she is paralysed. she knows not everyone can be trusted.

but, she 
she is herself.

text: my story from october 2016: it's easier to deny it, it's easier not to say anything, but, unfortunately that is what allows it to continue. this morning, this pervert passed behind me and touched my bum. it could sound funny but it is an act that happens too often. despite knowing this is not ok, i stood there and did nothing. what am i meant to do or say? i thought maybe it was an accident and he just brushed past in a hurry. i watched as he started talking to strangers. i just watched for 5 minutes and was ready to give up. my boyfriend comes back up the street and asks me why i look upset. i tell him and he walks directly over to the man to confront him. the pervert ignores him and walks away and talks to strangers again. it is very clear now that it was an intentional act and the pervert doesn't want to acknowledge anything. my boyfriend yells clearly that it is not acceptable to touch women like that. the strangers hear and are all shocked and the pervert walks away. i'm posting this to say it's not ok...to hope that my dear friends and family can stand up for themselves if it ever happens to them... to admit that i could have stood up for myself but i didn't, because of fear, embarrassment and shock but it's something i will learn... to say thank you to my boyfriend and to all of you out there who stand up for women and girls. we need you because sometimes we can't or aren't ready to stand up for ourselves.

text:
one year before the #metoo movement, i was fortunate enough to be part of the latin american #niunamenos mobilization in bolivia. the picture is from november 26 2016: i remember how, although separated from the crowd through the lense of my camera and my distance as an observing researcher, i still felt the power of the shouts of thousands: â€œni una menos, vivas nos queremosâ€ - â€œnot one woman less, we want us aliveâ€. it was a moment that not only changed my trajectory as a researcher, woman and person, but i think, it was catalyst for the global wave of bringing the violence against women and statesâ€™ ignorance in the face of it to light. i believe it was also the starting point for what sarah banet-weiser calls in her recent book â€œpopular feminismâ€. a feminism that was finally somehow socially excepted (but because of that also exploited by neoliberal logics with prints on t-shirtâ€™s, and advertising slogans). itâ€™s nothing new that the west fails to recognize the brave thinkers and activists from the so-called â€œglobal southâ€ who have often paved the path for the evolution of humanity for the good. 
although just a little step, iâ€™m happy to represent the movement tomorrow at the @uniofleicester â€™s â€œimages of research exhibitionâ€ from 11-4 pm in the fraser noble hall. if youâ€™re around, come see the print of this photo, and if you want, vote for the picture for the â€œpeopleâ€™s choice awardâ€. grateful to #niunamenosbolivia and @aluanelitta to permitting me to use her face that stands for her continuous fight for womenâ€™s lives ğŸ’œ

although just a little step, iâ€™m happy to represent the movement tomorrow at the @uniofleicester â€™s â€œimages of research exhibitionâ€ from 11-4 pm in the fraser noble hall. if youâ€™re around, come see the print of this photo, and if you want, vote for the picture for the â€œpeopleâ€™s choice awardâ€. grateful to #niunamenosbolivia and @aluanelitta to permitting me to use her face that stands for her continuous fight for womenâ€™s lives ğŸ’œ

text:
"i forgive you."
#thisisapainting
20 by 20â€ acrylic, december 2018
ğŸŒ«
some of the bullet holes i shot myself.  sometimes i am my own worst enemy.  sometimes it is myself that stands in the way of my future.
ğŸŒ«
this note was shot at, walked on, left in the rain, torn up, and held underwater.  for me the mistreatment is figurative, but for others it is a physical reality. ğŸŒ«
somehow, the words remain through it all.  strong and true as before the first act of destruction, as if nothing could stop them. ğŸŒ«
we all know how easy it is to forgive... these days forgiveness could be considered a revolutionary act. ğŸŒ«
clarity, freedom, and wholeness seem to come after those 3 important words: "i. forgive. you." maybe then we can move forward in kindness and peace with ourselves and one another.  may we act towards clarity as humans; we all have been hurt and mistreated, and may we allow ourselves the freedom to let go of the pain (with wisdom) and move forward towards unity and (dare i say it) love for ourselves and for one another. ğŸŒ«

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
via @aliyasking for @essence magazine.
.
.
in the summer of 1984, i was sexually assaulted by a 17-year-old camp counselor. i was 12 years old. the counselor was from my hometown and i saw him every day at camp and then every day in school for the next year until he graduated.
.
if i saw this man on the street today, would i say a word to him? absolutely not. would i visit his church? never. for me, this man is canceled. forever. since 1984. i wouldnâ€™t say i hate him, but i would never want anything to do with him, his family, his friends. i know exactly what canceling someone looks like and when it came to my abuser, i had no problem doing so.
.
if my attacker had been #rkelly, would i listen to his music? absolutely not. i wouldnâ€™t be able to stomach a single note. i wouldnâ€™t be able to watch his videos or see him perform. he would be canceled.
.
and yet i still listened to his music. why wouldnâ€™t i? the man has been called a musical genius, serving as a bridge from classic soul artists like #samcooke and #steviewonder. of course, celebrity worship has always been a tricky game. and one could argue that @rkelly was no different from so many others.... i separated the artist from the art.
.
i finally understand, this is exactly whatâ€™s happening to scores of black women who have reported that r. kelly abused them in various ways. these women live in a world that simply doesnâ€™t seem to care about their allegations. a world that separates the artistÂ  from the art.
.
.
right is right and wrong is wrong, and iâ€™m way late to this campaign. but better late than never, because power in numbers has always been the source of our progressâ€”from slave revolts to civil rights sit-ins to the #metoo movement. though i finally hit the #muterkelly button, it should have been sooner; i think many will say the same as the movement continues to grow. there is no room for nuance anymore. the truth is, there never was. so, for my daughtersâ€™ sake and for women everywhere, i will no longer separate the artist from his art. .
.

text:
between 25 november (the international day for the elimination of violence against women 2018) and 10 december (human rights day), the south african government (amongst others) marks sixteen days of activism for no violence against women and children. many of the most insidious forms of violence in south africa occur between intimate partners and in the home. dramatic need works with many vulnerable women and children using arts-based advocacy and community theatre to build awareness, self-confidence and help them to speak out against abuse and abusers. we also work with boys and young men to encourage them to better communicate and to express their anger and frustrations in a non-violent way. this form of psycosocial care is crucial if intimate partner violence is to be obliterated in future generations. to mark these 16 days of advocacy for no violence against women and children we will be posting short videos of women from all walks of life, from all round the world, highlighting the appalling statistics in south africa of violence against women and children. please share these videos with people you love. itâ€™s time for awareness and itâ€™s time for change. .
 #thisneedstochange #countmein #heremetoo #creativechange #womenspeakfacts#metoo#gbvmuststop #16days we acknowledge that gender-based violence exists in all communities, amongst all genders and affects both trans and cis-gendered people. we have specifically focused on women â€“ and those who identify as women â€“ and children during this campaign. dramatic need works in south africa and so this is where we have chosen to focus our advocacy. however, gender based violence of any form is abhorrent & we stand in solidarity with those who have experienced it, whatever their gender, wherever they are in the world. in these videos we have done our best to use reliable and verifiable statistics. where statistics were not measured within the last two years we have indicated this. sexual violence &rape statistics are difficult to accurately measure due to low levels of reporting and the intimacy of the crime. for more information about the sources of these statistics see our blog! thank you @radebenthabeleng !ğŸ§¡ğŸ§¡

text:
between the ages of 6 and 7, i was sexually assaulted. 
before i go any further, i want you to know that i donâ€™t need your sympathy or remorse. sharing my story has been something that i have thought about for the last 13 years, and recent circumstances in my life and in todayâ€™s society have compelled me to let this out. .
i remember at my orientation for college when the guides started talking about sexual assault- recent reports showed that 1 in 3 women have been raped, abused, drugged, or forced to do something against their own will. it didnâ€™t strike me as profound until i was in a recent conversation, and realized that i was that statistic. .
it has taken me this long to talk about it... to release... because i was scared. i was confused. i knew it was wrong. i donâ€™t want to go into graphic detail, but the feeling of being held against your will... fighting so hard to break free... only to give up and give in because you are powerless against a testosterone-fueled masculine figure is a gut wrenching circumstance that i donâ€™t wish upon anyone. .
those experiences were traumatic- being taken advantage of at such a young age, by someone who i shouldâ€™ve been able to trust. up until now, my family and very close friends were the only ones that i opened up to about this. the one thing that allowed me to cope was distracting myself with all things horses and riding. the first photo is for reference at how young i was when this happened.
.

the paris painting â€˜venus withinâ€™. which i am currently raising funds to help cover costs for participation in the 157th edition of the snba, it will be held in annex of the louvre in paris, france, taking place from 13 to 16 of december 2018. funds will be used for a variety of needs; shipping and travel fees of the artwork and for the artist to travel to the show.
the funds raised will also contribute to a whole series called â€˜indestructible womenâ€™, it will be displayed here in canada later in 2019 and is what i have always wanted my art and purpose to be about. to show women and the world, that their stories of â€˜indestructible womenâ€™ hold a place in history. permanently told through paint. for they are truly worthy of having their story inspire others. *please support and share*
i can do it with your help, but i can't do it alone. raising funds to be able to go with my painting to paris and to allow my other series to travel and be seen here in canada, and to especially bring it to the east coast, my home of both newfoundland and labrador. 'from labrador to paris and beyond.' go to:

text:
from the many sexual harassment cases in india in the recent past, the companies that have had to pay severely in terms of legal expenses, loss of reputation and even increase in attrition were the very ones that tried to bend the rules as per their convenience.
.
.
from trying to ignore or blame the victim to focusing on only waiting to redress workplace sexual harassment and not focusing on preventing it, many companies have goofed up due to their attitude of ticking compliance check-boxes as per their business needs.
.
.
but sexual harassment is more than a compliance issue, it is a serious human rights violation. and only when companies get serious about prevention of sexual harassment (posh) and show zero tolerance for the issue by going the extra mile with high-impact awarnesss programmes will they really be successful in stopping sexual harassment at their workplace.
.
be.artsy has successfully conducted art-based, highly effective posh programmes for companies such as pepsico, mediatek, amex, giesecke+devrient, and bt (british telecom). our current campaign itâ€™s not ok has raised awareness among more than 12,000 working professionals in 2018. for more information, please contact: shipra@be-artsy.com
.
.
.
.
#preventionofsexualharassment #workplacelaws #posh #beartsy #metoo #mentalassault #mentalharassment #instaworkplace #instaoffice #feminism #feminist #timesup #believesurvivors #womensreality #whyididntreport

text:
wall street has adopted a new strategy in the #metoo era: avoid women altogether.

call it the pence effect, after u.s. vice president mike pence, who says he avoids dining alone with any women who aren't his wife.

in finance, the impact could essentially be gender segregation, and wall street risks becoming even more of a boy's club, rather than less of one. â€œwomen are grasping for ideas on how to deal with it, because it is affecting our careers,â€ a senior vice president at wells fargo & co said. â€œitâ€™s a real loss.â€

princess @iamexceldoo speaks to us about the importance of teaching children to be confident. 
in many cases, self-esteem and domestic violence go hand in hand. low self-esteem can be brought on by a variety of factors and can be a serious issue for women (and men) who are victims of domestic violence.

contrary to what many believe, domestic violence is not just about physical violence. it can also include sexual abuse, emotional abuse, financial abuse, and stalking. basically, domestic violence offenders always feel the need to be in control of their victims. the less in control an offender feels, the more they want to hurt others.

text:
i had a close friend tell me that if i wanted to travel i should go alone. he doesn't have a problem travelling alone, he is a 6'6 white man. i didn't know how to explain that as a woman half his size, the world is a lot more dangerous. 
i don't think i have travelled to a single place where i have not experienced some sort of sexual harassment or worse. 
i have been picked up off the ground three times(jamaica, cuba), once the guy started to run with me(bratislava). i have been locked in a hotel room(barcelona). i had a man walk up to me in broad daylight and shove his tongue down my throat (paris) even had my shirt ripped and my breast bit in the middle of the sidewalk(nyc). sure, that was then, this is now. but has the world changed? i still can't walk to the corner store without being catcalled or followed. how am i supposed to travel to a foreign place, where maybe i can't speak the language to defend myself or tell anyone of something were to happen. even worse, what if my status as a tourist leaves me in a position where the attacker has the upper hand? 
#words #wordoftheday #empathy #love #thoughful #metoo

text:
yes he can. ğŸ‘Š  we're holding on. ğŸ™  thank you in advance god. again. *i've been thinking lately about how i filter my life for instagram, as most people do, and i feel led to share why i do it. 
its not because i want you to think my life is perfect, nobody's is. i post "good stuff" because you can scroll around your social media and easily find reasons to be angry, sad, depressed, jealous or unworthy, and i want to share things that will help you feel good.  god's love,  encouragement, a funny,  an exercise, yummy food, and fun ideas. 
i have a good life, yes, but like everyone i have my challenges too and i've overcome a lot in the past. here's a short list, and if you need some encouragement in any area, please reach out.  i'm here for you. â¤ - i can say #metoo at least a dozen times
- i was drugged and almost raped when i was 17
- my first husband was abusive in every way, i left the night it got physical, christmas actually
- i was single for 10 years after that and it wasnt always fun and easy
- i overcame an eating disorder
- i made some bad choices when i was younger
- i've seen divorce from every angle
- i'm still getting settled in this new town of my new life
- aside from my family, i feel without purpose here sometimes
- the boys' mom isn't happy i'm in the picture and it doesn't have to be this hard. â¤ but, you know what?  god. he's shown himself bigger than every situation i've given him and he'll continue to. ğŸ™

text:
#morningmessage #ohmomgod #metoo #christed #mominshaman 
i am often told that my words are "fancy" i use them the way i was taught to. i was taught some great lessons by people that were miserable. i have also learned some great lessons about peace. learning to love in a hateful world is a challenge. i have been lied to, tricked and deceived by those that processes undying love for me. in the process i have been able to be an example to people that have no idea what god's love is like. we give compassion so readily for the visible ills of the world and miss the pain in our own heart. then someone comes along to see something in us that we don't see within ourselves. god is real and we have our own relationship. i believe in love and caring for those who care for me, praying for those that will not communicate with me and being at peace with the fact that i am the only one i can control. i do however influence the energy around me. turning a frown upside down and seeing beauty in the world around me.

text:
my routine has changed. i have to wakeup at 6 and come back home around 7.  i am only girl in my department and is always being checked out ğŸ˜„.
i am learning and trying new things, making new friends. i am being more confident everyday when i walk through the crowd full of just men. i pretend to ignore even when i know some person is trying to approach me. 
amidst all of this, i am enjoyng every single bit of it. i laugh at my ownself, feel good, do something that scares me. i am loving myseld more. these are the perks of having an outclass job and getting transferred to 3rd city within an year. 
i am exploring myself. i am much stronger than you think. i am much more fierce than you think. i am everything you think i cant be or i am not. i am not a shy little pretty looking girl while i am the most confident. i am woman among men but i am def one of them. i am all that they are and they cant defeat me. when i enter my office and take those stairs made of black marble that shines so bright and take my seat to the moment i come back, exit my office, i m a new person. i am some one new who doesnâ€™t need anyone. she is all enough for her ownself.
p.s: you never know your strength until you test yourself. never push yourself back from hardships. it is the main thing that makes you stronger.
p.p.s: this is self-appreciation post. donâ€™t bother to read it if you criticize it. .

text: #metoo the midrash that supposedly started the chanukah rebelion tells the tale that the emperor of jerusalem would have the brides spend their first night of marriage with him. he would unbashfully take the brides first encounter, which was shattering for our entire nation - both the brides and the grooms. one brave daughter protested by standing undressed in front of the nation, when they were horrified she said - if i can't stand like this in front of my bothers then why should i stand like this in front of our cruel greek leader? for the first time, the jewish men understood her and took a risky stand. they walked her to the palace, attacked, cut off the emperors head and stopped this horrific tradition. however this move started the war and conflict that chanukah is all about. this chanukah story taught me that taking a stand to sexual assault has been a part of our nation since the very beginning. our jewish men risked their lives and stopped this horrific attacks on the beautiful brides. i love that this issue is what started our chanukah revolution. it sort off reminds of today, the revolution that is taking place and the miracle that we can speak up. we no longer have to stand up to our entire nation in order to tell our story. we live in a time where we can talk about what we experienced without feeling guilty or shamed. this is such a blessing.  only a survivor knows how truly comforting it is. this freedom is a little flame that really does bring light to a chamber of darkness. i am proud for my daughter and our sons that they will be living in a world with more acceptance, more love and more tolerance, and please god as oprah says - a world where they will no longer have to say me too. || top and scarf by @mimumaxi

can you feel it?
some of you might remember how less than a month ago i told that i had a trauma anniversary (20 years). well, when i took this ferry ride on wednesday, it was the first time i was on a same kind of a cabin than where it happened when i was 14. might have even been the exact same ferry, as it was the same company anyway. i was nervous about spending the night there, alone with no internet connection which is my trusted distraction. i for sure didn't choose to sleep on the same bed but on the other side. but. then i realized this is again my opporturnity to take back of what belongs to me and was never his to use, and to me that comes naturally through photos. so i sat naked on that bed, same side of where it happened, and i said fuck you and felt a bit more empowered again. i am a fucking warrior so screw you, asshole.ğŸ–•ğŸ¼

text:
#day7 of the #whiteribboncampaign #16daysofactivism ğŸ— (dec. 1, 2018) 
70% of spousal violence is not reported to the police. ğŸš“

why not? 
one of the primary reasons women donâ€™t come forward to report sexual harassment or assault is shame. shame is at the core of the intense emotional wounding women and men experience when they are sexually violated. 
this sense of shame often causes victims to blame themselves for the sexual misconduct of their perpetrator.

this tendency to blame themselves and to be overwhelmed with shame leads to the next important reason why women donâ€™t come forward: denial and minimization. 
many women refuse to believe that the treatment they endured was actually abusive. they downplay how much they have been harmed by sexual harassment and even sexual assault. they convince themselves that â€œit wasnâ€™t a big deal.â€ ğŸ™ğŸ½ and finally, women convince themselves that they are the only victim of a sexual harasser or abuser. it is often only after other women step forward to say that they were abused by a perpetrator that a victim may realize that they are dealing with a serial abuser or pedophile. #metoo

fear of the repercussions is a huge obstacle women face when it comes to reporting sexual harassment or assault â€” fear of losing their job, fear they wonâ€™t find another job, fear they will be passed over for a promotion, fear of losing their credibility, fear of being branded a troublemaker, fear of being blackballed in their industry, fear of their physical safety.

many donâ€™t disclose because they fear they wonâ€™t be believed, and until very recently, that has primarily been the case. the fact that sexual misconduct is the most under-reported crime is due to a common belief that women make up these stories for attention or to get back at a man who rejected them. victims' accounts are often scrutinized to the point of exhaustion. in high-profile cases, victims are often labeled opportunists, blamed for their own victimization, and punished for coming forward. 
there are so many reasons why a survivor of gender-based violence may choose not to report. whatever their reason is, respect their decision and their reasons for it.

text: imagine you are a teenage girl growing up in zimbabwe; you have a one in three chance of being married by age 18, and the same odds of being a victim of physical violence. one in six of your friends already has a baby, two-thirds of your neighbors live in poverty. when you are in your early 20s, you will be three times as likely as your male peers to be hiv-positive. in many communities it is difficult for girls to protect themselves from violence, manipulation, abuse and of course hiv -- a disease that has infected 14% of the adult population. usaid dreams partnership is an ambitious project to reduce hiv infections among adolescent girls and young women in 10 sub-saharan african countries. the goal of dreams is to help girls develop into determined, resilient, empowered, aids-free, mentored and safe women. read more on the power of girls stories forging a brighter future in zimbabwe. #16days #endgbv  #zimbabwe #endaids #endaids2030 #child #women #girlsnotbrides #endchildmarriage #marriage #wedding #activists #childlabour #rapeculture#rape #blamethevictim #abuse #metoo #feminism #sexualabuse #rapevictim #rapeculture #sex  #domesticviolence #survivor #nomore #victim  #whyididntreport

text:
today. i'm excited to meet this girl. she's an exceptional lady that went through some crazy trauma in her past. 
despite it all - she continues to be a pillar in advocating for children's rights as she prepares to make the wrong that was done to her in the past, a right so that the generations going forward can reap the seeds she's sown. 
today i'm going to meet a mother who continues to push through her ptsd so she can pave a safe environment for her daughters. 
despite having been sexual abused through her childhood and adolescence - she continues to fill herself up with self-compassion, self-awareness and self-esteem so she may be the best mother, daughter, wife and friend that she can be.

today i'm going to meet an extraordinary woman. and i promise you she will be my best friend.

that woman is me.

text:
cw: sexual violence

kathmandu, 2018: more than thirty years after the namita-sunita murders, nepal erupted in protests over the still unsolved rape and murder case of 13 year old nirmala pant. mass demonstrations were held across the country including nuwakot, kavre, jhapa, morang, and banke districts. the attendees came from all walks of life and included children. one teenage boy was killed and dozens injured in west nepal when police opened fire on protesters.

photograph by sanjog manandhar for kathmandu post depicting durga devi pant, the mother of nirmala, addressing a rally demanding #justice at new baneshwor in kathmandu in september 2018. text extracted from news reports by the kathmandu post and al jazeera

while at the "man up: unpacking masculinity" panel at the teen vogue summit, crews addressed the issue of toxic masculinity, and spoke about the significance of accountability. "i think as men, what we need to do is to say, 'we're sorry.' then we need to concede, and then we need to be accountable," the actor explained. "the person who molested me in 2016, i had already forgiven him. that wasn't the point. the point was like, 'wait, wait, you're telling me you can just do it? you're telling me, wait, it's okay? you're not going to do anything?' he's like, 'no, i said i was sorry.' i said, 'but you're not going to correct this? i'm giving you guys millions of dollars and you're going to sit here and say, 'well, terry, you're less of a human being right now. just a little bit less. just say it.' i'm, like, 'i'm not saying that.'" the actor went on to reveal his decision to be a part of the #metoo movement, despite the criticisms of others. "you have to correct," he said. "you can't ignore me, i'm standing right here...yeah, i am. and all i did, this was not waving flags, this was not shooting guns in the air, this was like, 'no, no, no, you're not going to do that.' no, he can't go back to work. no. he can't go back to work and do that. no man, woman, child â€” you cannot molest anybody and go back to work." #jusswaggtv #jstv #idjswagg #atl #terrycrews #teensummit #metoo #radio

text:
3 years back ,i thought , i can be a model and i started applying in whatever website i could find in google.

there were few direct questions from few of the people in the glam model world  which i found extremely demeaning , well, ya even i faced multiple times situation which was disgusting .

but today, i am not here to recall any metoo moment , i am here to tell that, we cannot and we should not generalize everyone based on some situation in our life.
i want everyone to be careful but still believe that goodness is there , not all people are bad.
i want everyone, specially girls to be careful but still listen to your intuition .

listen to your inner voice and adhere to it. if it's saying - don't go ,something is wrong ..please don't go.

if you feel good , go ahead , explore , trust .not all human are same , not all figures are same. .
.
tag a girl who may be more scared from the stories of metoo movement.
.

text:
almost â€“ a terrifying true story of an innocent boy who survived twenty years of abuse. â€œonce i realised who was responsible, my daily life was consumed with thoughts of revenge.â€ sexually abused at five, seven and twelve years of age, shikesh was unaware that he would end up suffering so much more than he had already experienced.

growing up without living a normal childhood, teenage hood and even an early adulthood, he realised what mattered the most; to find happiness in his own unique way.

shikesh understood that his journey to recovery was going to be very painful and prepared himself for the fight of his life.

in almost, shikesh tells his empowering story as he develops a deep self-awareness of why it is important to give our own meaning to a new beginning.

available here:Â https://amzn.to/2koaxel

our culture is so "familiar" that it leaves too many grey areas that open doors to be inappropriate.

so many of us excuse inappropriate behavior because "a suh dem stay" or we laugh it off because we are the only female in the room.
then there are other females that laugh and giggle like being inappropriate is to be encouraged.

i guess jamaica is too small for a movement like #metoo because we will be blacklisted or worse ridiculed and told that we are liars.

dec 3 // a note she wrote on china jasmine // it was early in the summer, before the party season had reached a true crescendo, when the sisters made a pact - we need not know his name to fall in love and, he need not know we are twins. what began with a series of â€˜strangely timed happeningsâ€™ soon settled into a state of â€˜how things just areâ€™. these were the words their mother used and on reflection she had egged the girls on. jasmine and china leung, identical twins, unable to be told apart, had chosen the man they would marry. the girls had meet him at the tea party of a cousins, cousin, set amongst a garden of dense ramble and dripping wisteria, so filled was the gathering with anyone and everyone looking for love. people appeared and disappeared, no one ever stood still, the air buzzed with frenetic, early summer blush. and the girls, drank this in, floated about and could easily be mistaken, easily assumed that jasmine and china were one and the same. one girl. and so invitations to dinner began to arrive addressed to miss jasmine china and their egging mother, being mercenary of heart saw in her tea leaves a two for one offer, a single wedding, a single dowery and a very, very happy husband. @t2tea

text:
as a rape survivor, i tend to be sensitive to violence or sexual assault against women shown in films, on tv programmes, books, etc. in many cases it seems so graphic and unnecessary, and can even help normalise misogynistic behaviour. for instance, i was a massive fan of game of thrones until several seasons in when i just couldn't bare the rape scenes any further. i haven't watched since. you don't see men or boys portrayed in the same ways in tv, films and books as often as you do women and girls.

what are your thoughts on this? is sexual abuse and violence against women too mainstream? should directors and writers take a step back and remove unnecessarily misogynistic behaviour and plots from the arts? then there is porn culture, which is opening up an entirely different can of worms. i'd love to hear your thoughts.

#rapeculture #survivorsnotvictims #media #metoo #hollywood #thearts #endviolenceagainstwomen #endsexualviolence #vawg #stopmisogyny #misogyny #feminism #timesup #changetheculture #change #womensrights #genderequality #gameofthrones

happy birthday to the beautiful warrior that i am so proud to call my friend, @carlsbadfawcett!!!!!!!!!
you are such a glittering gemstone of passion, love, talent, strength, and courage. you have the heart of a lion, and the claws of one, too! it has truly been a wonder watching each other grow as artists, friends, feminists, and lovers of the silver screen since meeting in august 2017. there is no one i would rather show around tinsel town than you, which is why i am counting down the days until you visit la for new yearâ€™s!
you can bet iâ€™m sketching out an action packed itinerary of must-see things to see and do to fill your trip with ecstatic magic in the greatest city on the edge of the world! 
we will dance on the sand and fall in love with the ocean under a moonlit night to ring in the best new year yet! ğŸŒ™ğŸŒŠâœ¨ğŸğŸŒƒ today also marks my love britney spearsâ€™ birthday, whose song â€˜stronger,â€™ inspired the poster i created for the toronto metoo march with you! we got birthdays galore on such a seriously special day!
there is so magic waiting for you here in the city of angels, so come lasso in the stars with me.
.
some flashbacks here of us prepping for the metoo march 12/02/17.
how blessed are we to be alive!!!!!!!
like crazy!

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

foreign body

synopsis: foreign body is the beautifully crafted solo show about hope, healing and forgiveness after sexual assault. uniquely told from the perspective of the survivor and perpetrator of the same assault, using a charged combination of verbatim, physical theatre and a stunning original soundtrack, foreign body is a brave, liberating and life-affirming story. the play aims to destigmatize dialogue around sexual violence and offers audience members the opportunity to explore the playâ€™s themes through a post-show panel discussion alongside sector specialists.

@regran_ed from @warif_ng -  day 9 | december 03

rapists rape. 
the accountability and the shame lies with them and them alone and not  with the survivor.

and the rest of us? we have a role to play too. we can no longer be bystanders watching as these acts occur in our homes, schools, offices and neighborhoods. we need to intervene and be our brother and sisters keepers. stand up and defend the more vulnerable and oppressed in our society. it is our collective responsibility to do so. 
see something? say something! 
save a life today.

share our stories , repost , tag someone and join us in the #orangetheworldwithwarif campaign as we participate in the #16daysofactivism against gender based violence.

and the rest of us? we have a role to play too. we can no longer be bystanders watching as these acts occur in our homes, schools, offices and neighborhoods. we need to intervene and be our brother and sisters keepers. stand up and defend the more vulnerable and oppressed in our society. it is our collective responsibility to do so. 
see something? say something! 
save a life today.

share our stories , repost , tag someone and join us in the  campaign as we paicipate in the  against gender based violence.

text:
just this year i found myself saving a scrapbook of ideas which included lingerie fashion shoots for high end magazines. i was drawn to them so much, because they were there to sell lingerie to womenâ€¦not necessarily men. they were elegant and feminine, i felt i could respectably portray a woman in this very style without over sexualising them. fashionable, luxurious, empowering and beautiful.

in august this year i put my heart into launching my boudoir photography for women. as i talk with all the women who were getting their make up done before a shoot, i realised they were here for themselves. not to necessarily gift a man the photos, but to do this for themselves. i found there has been deeper reasons why these amazing women felt like a boudoir shoot will help them feel empowered and strong again. each woman has a story to tell. each woman has overcome an obstacle in their life which has been a struggle. each woman has been strong and persistent to move forward, however they can to work through understanding themselves and confidently standing on their own two feet again.

my heart feels sad when i hear their stories, but as women we are also here to support and help our sisters move forward. i have gotten so much more out of just being a â€œboudoir photographerâ€ than i thought. i have gotten so much out of speaking with you all. and i am hoping i can be here to help in some way or another for you to discover and love yourself again. through kind words from the time we get to spend in the studio or from you looking at your images and being proud of the woman you have become after your battles you fought to get there. i hope i make the slightest difference in a positive way.

broken hearts, stretch marks, loss of loved ones, body transformations, raising children on your own. you all have inspiring stories that have moved me and made me thankful that i have taken this path in my photography to meet you and also help me be a better person too. remember you are amazing and you are beautiful. scars are unique. curves are beautiful. but your smile and self respect are the most important. thank you for trusting me and sharing your stories. renee xx

womenâ€™s work highlights historic, modern and contemporary work by women in the southwarkâ€™s art collection.
2018 has been an important year for raising issues about womenâ€™s equality and recognition. there are many powerful stories, from the centenary of womenâ€™s partial suffrage in 1918 to the #metoo movement. this exhibition makes visible a selection of female artists and raises questions about the structures that impact the ways in which women artists are represented, displayed and collected.

featured artists include margaret sarah carpenter, prunella clough, anya gallaccio, grace golden, barbara hepworth, sarah lucas, saskia olde wolbers and bertha newcombe.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: i have very personal reasons for supporting the #iloendgbv campaign. i was one of those women that experienced a sexual assault in the workplace and was unfairly dismissed shortly there after by the man who assaulted me. yes. it happened to #metoo. and it happened at a humanitarian organisation. sexual assauat, exploitation and harrassment don't only happen in the entertainment industry or on the factory floors of south east asia #aidtoo. and we're just as bad at dealing with this challenge as the rest of the world even when we're trying to be better than the rest of the world and make the rest of the world a better. i know. the irony. while there are many layers to the solution the #iloendgbv convention is an important piece of the tool kit we need to develop and use to create the future we envisage where all people are safe in public and in private spaces. the ilo sets the global standards and their response to this years #metoo moment couldn't have come at a better time. @womenscentreng #wcc2018 and  i support this initiative and encourage all #afrifem sisters to support the #iloendgbv convention. recent revelations from the african union have undoubtedly stirred up activity on the continent already. we can do this. yes we can #16daysofactivism

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
introducing patrick mu'a as cupid.

which reindeer do you play, and how would you describe them in just three words.

cupid - fierce, fabulous and fun

have you been naughty or nice this year?

always naughty darling, what kind of question is thatğŸ˜‰

if you had to be trapped in a christmas movie, which one would you choose?

rent the musical: the film

one christmas wish that you think santa claus should grant this year?

eliminate homophobia... or stilettos in hooves sizes please.

what does this play make you reconsider about christmas?

that christmas shouldnâ€™t be an excuse to push all family issues aside and that not everyone will have the picture perfect image of christmas.

what do you hope audiences take away from this play?

that this play is very relevant to what has been happening in society foreverrrrr and finally has been shone a light on thanks to movements likeÂ â€ª#metoo. human stories of chemical dependencies and botched suicide attempts and repressed memories of sexual and child molestation... but with a holiday twist.

donâ€™t miss seeing patrick as cupid in the eight: reindeer monologues.Â 
blackbox theatre, nambour
december 8, 2pm and 7.30pm.Â 
tickets on sale now at www.firelighttheatre.com.au

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
