text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like â€˜drain the swampâ€™ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the â€˜deep stateâ€™ that werenâ€™t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman

just because you did something wrong in the past doesn't mean you can't advocate for it now. you made a mistake and learned from it. you grew! do not let people hold it against you as you try to do the right thing now

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
trigger warning: suicidal thoughts, rape
to any survivor of rape or sexual assault who has thought about committing suicide - you are not alone. 
33% women who have been raped contemplate suicide and 13% attempt suicide.
i know what it feels like to feel there is no hope left, to feel there is nothing worth living for or like a part of you already died. i know because i felt it myself, and i am so sorry you are in that place.
a part of me does feel like i already died on december 1st, 2017 and this scared stranger has just been inhabiting my body for the past year.

i googled how to kill myself more than once.
i got 279,000,000 in 0.30 seconds.
while i was searching for the most painless and efficient way to die, i totaled the mg of all the medications i had in my possession and posed a straight forward question: if i took all my medication at once, would i just go to sleep and never wake up?
luckily, finding the answer to that question was not easy and the information i obtained prevented me from making that choice.
i'd be more likely to end up in the hospital with permanent organ and brain damage and alive. 
i found websites that told me combining the drugs with a use of a plastic bag over the head would increase the chances of death drastically. 
in this place, i started to view suicide as a solution to the problems that being raped created. but that's the thing, that reality will not change whether you are dead or alive. if anything, it meant people would permanently associate my trauma with the ending of myself. 
remember: suicide is preventable and suicidal thoughts are temporary.
if you are feeling suicidal ask yourself one question: have i always felt like i do right now? the chance is, there were times in your life when you did not. which means something in your life changed to get you where you are now. but that also means that something else can change to get you away from where you are now.
please reach out to someone for help.it doesn't even have to be someone you know. reach out to the national suicide prevention lifeline at 1-800-273-8255.
you can survive this.
please leave a â¤ in the comment if you made it this far.

i'd be more likely to end up in the hospital with permanent organ and brain damage and alive. 
i found websites that told me combining the drugs with a use of a plastic bag over the head would increase the chances of death drastically. 
in this place, i staed to view suicide as a solution to the problems that being raped created. but that's the thing, that reality will not change whether you are dead or alive. if anything, it meant people would permanently associate my trauma with the ending of myself. 
remember: suicide is preventable and suicidal thoughts are temporary.
if you are feeling suicidal ask yourself one question: have i always felt like i do right now? the chance is, there were times in your life when you did not. which means something in your life changed to get you where you are now. but that also means that something else can change to get you away from where you are now.
please reach out to someone for help.it does not even have to be someone you know. reach out to the national suicide prevention lifeline at 1-800-273-8255.
you can survive this.
please leave a â¤ in the comment if you made it this far.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

cw: sexual violence

kathmandu 1981: the namita-sunita murders are stamped indelibly into public memory because it was the first time nepali women had organized to protest against rape. women didn't only chant slogans against rape at the protest #rally and mass gathering organized by all nepal women's association; women's representative groups also submitted petitions to the government.Â women had organized for women and they were protesting on behalf of women.Â protests were raised in sessions of the national legislative assembly, rashtriya panchayat to make accurate information regarding the murders public.

photograph and text from 'voicing the silence: sexual violence and public memory', part of an exhibition presented by @photoktm at the chhaya center in thamel. the multi-chaper exhibition is called 'the public life of women: a feminist memory project' and aims to 'memorialize women's pasts in the belief that their historical visibility will advance the case for liberation'

text:
about mothers,sisters, daughters and friends- saptmatripa.
manifestations inspire me to attempt to analyze the world i see around me, 
especially as a woman who must make sense, daily 
of injustices in the world. 
to comprehend why we continue to look away when prejudice occurs, 
when sensitivities corrode, or when negative forces are invoked. 
i, therefore, look inwards 
to evoke the energy that is manifest in each one of us
to apply the healing salve of motherhood to a world that needs it. 
for that energy resides in each one of us 
women and men 
crossing all genders 
and it is that i must manifest..

text:
for so long i suffered and stumbled along in the darkness,
i found my comfort in the bottom of a bottle, my only happiness.
i couldnâ€™t stand what i saw staring back at me in the mirror,
depression, anxiety, ptsd so severe.
then someone came along and showed me another way, 
that light at the end of the tunnel and hope for a new day.
so many positive changes happening all around, 
but most importantly the amazing changes within were profound. 
i was embarking on this new and exciting journey,
discovering who i was and what life really meant to me.
for the first time in my life i finally found internal peace,
all that trauma, the nightmares, and memories i was able to release. 
it was like i was given a second chance to start life all over again, 
unlearning everything that i had known, breaking free from those chains.
one year on and so many great things are happening,
i feel so much stronger, although there are lessons, i am still learning.
my circle has changed, with some heartbreak along the way,
but here i stand, filled with light, love, and happiness today.

that light at the end of the tunnel and hope for a new day.
so many positive changes happening all around, 
but most importantly the amazing changes within were profound. 
i was embarking on this new and exciting journey,
discovering who i was and what life really meant to me.
for the first time in my life i finally found internal peace,
all that trauma, the nightmares, and memories i was able to release. 
it was like i was given a second chance to start life all over again, 
unlearning everything that i had known, breaking free from those chains.
one year on and so many great things are happening,
i feel so much stronger, although there are lessons, i am still learning.
my circle has changed, with some heartbreak along the way,
but here i stand, filled with light, love, and happiness today.
